\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Chapters 5 and 6 investigated fire weather variability in Victoria, Australia.
 The research used the McArthur Forest Fire Danger Index (FFDI) to explore
 this variability.
 The chapters proposed—and tested—the Victorian Seasonal Bushfire Index
 (VSBI).
 The VSBI is a forecasting tool and alternative fire weather metric.
 The last two chapters also examined the relationship between remote climate
 drivers and bushfires.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter investigates fire weather in Ecuador.
 The tropical Andes endures severe impacts from bushfire activity.
 However, this is one of the regions with fewer studies about fire weather.
 Ecuador and Victoria share the Eucalyptus as the dominant species in the
 bushfire-prone areas.
 Therefore, the investigation also uses the FFDI because its calibration
 used this vegetation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Data and methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Weather station
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study required weather station (WS) data from the Ecuadorian Andean
 region.
 Complete daily records were available only for six stations for the period
 1997-2012.
 Figure xxx shows the location of the stations.
 Each of the stations provided data on an eight-hourly basis.
 The hour selected for the computations was 1 p.m.
 local time (GMT 18:00).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Reanalysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This investigation used the two reanalysis products also analysed in previous
 chapters.
 These datasets are version two of the Twentieth Century Reanalysis Project
 (20CR) 
