LatexCommand citep
key "Compo2011"

\end_inset

 and the ERA-20C reanalysis from the European Reanalysis of Global Climate
 Observations ERA-Clim project (citations).
 Chapters 5 and 6 provide further details about these datasets.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Methodology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Analysis of fire weather variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aim of this study is to explore long-term trends in fire weather variability.
 However, the length of the weather station records in Ecuador is rather
 short.
 Therefore, this investigation applies methods described in previous chapters
 to extend the analysis.
 The first step was to compare the reanalysis data against observations.
 Plotting probability density functions (PDFs) and seasonal time series
 facilitated the analysis.
 The PDFs allowed to examine the distribution of data and detect deviations
 from the mean.
 The time series allowed comparing trends, magnitudes and correlate data.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The variables that showed significant deviations from the mean were bias-correct
ed.
 The bias-correction used linear scaling techniques.
 The application of additive and multiplicative linear scaling was useful
 to correct the biases.
 For relative humidity, the variables required for its calculation were
 bias-corrected for its recalculation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Fire weather variability computation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The investigation explored fire weather variability in Ecuador using the
 FFDI.
 This index was selected because its calibration used the Eucalyptus vegetation
 (see Chapter 2).
 This type of vegetation is dominant in bushfire prone areas in Ecuador
 (see Chapter 2).
 The index was computed for July-August-September (JAS).
 These months represent the more intense fire season in the Ecuadorian Andean
 region (see Chapter 2).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The computation of the FFDI in Ecuador used original and bias-corrected
 reanalysis data.
 As in the previous step, plotting PDFs and time series allowed to examine
 the computed FFDI data.
 The analyses also compared the results using weather station and reanalysis
 data.
 The PDFs used daily data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, the comparison of time series required defining a seasonal
 metric of the FFDI.
 Previous chapters used two metrics.
 The cumulative sum of daily values (FFDIcum) and the number of days with
 FFDI greater than 25 (FFDI>25).
 This analysis used only the FFDIcum metric.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:PDFs-variables-original-data"

\end_inset

 presents PDFs of fire weather variables.
 The figure compares weather station with original reanalysis data.
 The figure also shows the deviations from the mean for each variable.
 The 20CR data present larger deviations than ERA-20C for maximum temperature
 and relative humidity.
 In comparison to observations, maximum temperature deviates 9.2 oC (20CR)
 and 2.3 oC (ERA-20C).
 Relative humidity show biases of 11.4% (20CR) and 2.2% (ERA-20CR).
 On the other hand, the discrepancies are greater for wind speed and precipitati
on with the ERA-20C data.
 Wind speed shows deviations from the mean of 7.6 Km/h (ERA-20C) and 5.7 Km/h
 (20CR).
 For precipitation, the biases are 13.4 mm (ERA-20C) and 4 mm (20CR).
\end_layout

